00:02:47.430 --> 00:02:57.790
So Choregie is a name which
somehow comes from Greek.

00:02:57.790 --> 00:03:03.550
Old Greek tragedies and
chorics are supposed to be

00:03:03.550 --> 00:03:05.350
[? patrons. ?]

00:03:05.350 --> 00:03:07.900
And new music, which
is always together

00:03:07.900 --> 00:03:12.520
with Choregie, new music
theater refers to new music,

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:14.260
which I usually perform.

00:03:14.260 --> 00:03:18.910
And it's mostly music of our
time, contemporary music.

00:03:18.910 --> 00:03:21.820
But sometimes, new
music is also something

00:03:21.820 --> 00:03:26.260
which is rarely, or maybe even
never heard on our concert

00:03:26.260 --> 00:03:31.540
stages, such as medieval
music, or maybe ethnical music,

00:03:31.540 --> 00:03:35.930
or music which was taken for
some different context, such as

00:03:35.930 --> 00:03:38.290
sociological or--

00:03:38.290 --> 00:03:43.870
I don't know, maybe music
by women in monasteries,

00:03:43.870 --> 00:03:47.430
or anything like that, which
are not usually at the concert

00:03:47.430 --> 00:03:49.390
programs.

00:03:49.390 --> 00:03:55.270
So the theater nowadays is
still very much perceived only

00:03:55.270 --> 00:03:57.250
as drama theater.

00:03:57.250 --> 00:04:00.040
So while Indian
theater, Kathakali,

00:04:00.040 --> 00:04:02.560
or maybe Japanese theater--

00:04:02.560 --> 00:04:08.320
Noh, for example-- are
structured from dance, music,

00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:12.790
choral singing, stylized
rituals, and text,

00:04:12.790 --> 00:04:17.140
the main characteristic of
Western theater is that content

00:04:17.140 --> 00:04:20.440
is illustrated by drama--

00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:22.150
acting.

00:04:22.150 --> 00:04:25.810
But when people talk
about music theater,

00:04:25.810 --> 00:04:31.570
we automatically think of
opera, operetta, or musical,

00:04:31.570 --> 00:04:33.880
or music comedy.

00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:37.360
So with years of working
with Carmina Slovenika

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:38.500
and Kebataola--

00:04:38.500 --> 00:04:41.200
these are my two ensembles--

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:45.820
I developed a new
concept of music theater,

00:04:45.820 --> 00:04:48.730
which is sometimes also
called vocal theater

00:04:48.730 --> 00:04:52.090
or theater of voices.

00:04:52.090 --> 00:04:54.730
What is Choregie nowadays?

00:04:54.730 --> 00:04:56.470
It represents two fields--

00:04:56.470 --> 00:05:02.170
concept of principles how to
create music theater projects,

00:05:02.170 --> 00:05:07.570
and specific method of working
with ensembles, choirs,

00:05:07.570 --> 00:05:12.280
orchestras, actors, conductors.

00:05:12.280 --> 00:05:15.970
So for idea about
Choregie, I would like

00:05:15.970 --> 00:05:19.690
to share with you one clip now.

00:05:19.690 --> 00:05:23.350
It is one of my
earliest works named

00:05:23.350 --> 00:05:28.360
"From Time Immemorial," which
was performed, for a change,

00:05:28.360 --> 00:05:30.070
with opera--

00:05:30.070 --> 00:05:33.100
chorus and opera, orchestra
and opera soloists--

00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:36.220
which is quite a rare occasion
for music theater pieces,

00:05:36.220 --> 00:05:38.620
because as you know,
opera houses tend

00:05:38.620 --> 00:05:43.360
to keep their museums
with Verdi and Puccini.

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:47.680
And contemporary music is only
sometimes on the repertory,

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:50.420
just to be big.

00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:52.740
So please-- "From
Time Immemorial."

00:05:52.740 --> 00:05:55.734
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:05:55.734 --> 00:05:58.728
[MUSIC PLAYING]

