00:07:29.830 --> 00:07:30.740
[END PLAYBACK]

00:07:30.740 --> 00:07:37.020
So Choregie is composed of
elements that do not illustrate

00:07:37.020 --> 00:07:39.090
or double each other.

00:07:39.090 --> 00:07:42.960
So they somehow preserve
their own identity,

00:07:42.960 --> 00:07:46.290
and do not rely on
convention or hierarchy

00:07:46.290 --> 00:07:48.390
of elements in theater.

00:07:48.390 --> 00:07:52.590
I can explain this like
that-- if you have a dish,

00:07:52.590 --> 00:07:57.160
like a piece of meat,
maybe, and music,

00:07:57.160 --> 00:08:01.110
and you can put some side dishes
as a garnish, a little bit

00:08:01.110 --> 00:08:06.400
of vegetables-- that light, a
little bit of potato costumes.

00:08:06.400 --> 00:08:11.070
That's the way how, very
often, music theater projects

00:08:11.070 --> 00:08:12.330
are conceived.

00:08:12.330 --> 00:08:14.940
So we have like a major
thing, or maybe in drama,

00:08:14.940 --> 00:08:18.150
you have texts, and then you
add movement, or whatever.

00:08:18.150 --> 00:08:20.580
But for Choregie,
it is important

00:08:20.580 --> 00:08:22.380
that all elements are equal.

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:25.350
So we don't have a main
dish and side dishes.

00:08:28.800 --> 00:08:34.140
In music, the score is in
direct control of the musician.

00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:37.830
So the reception of the
execution of a music piece

00:08:37.830 --> 00:08:41.679
depends only on
musician initiatives.

00:08:41.679 --> 00:08:45.570
But this doesn't apply for
music in Choregie gear projects,

00:08:45.570 --> 00:08:48.030
because this music
requires from musician

00:08:48.030 --> 00:08:51.810
and the audience a completely
different experience--

00:08:51.810 --> 00:08:56.700
namely, the intensive radiation
of heard music or word

00:08:56.700 --> 00:09:00.630
is complemented with
culture of the scene--

00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:04.770
the culture of the eye, the
feeling of external form.

00:09:04.770 --> 00:09:09.330
So music becomes interesting
in a different way

00:09:09.330 --> 00:09:13.830
as it gets these references
in non-musical world.

00:09:13.830 --> 00:09:15.030
Why I'm telling this?

00:09:15.030 --> 00:09:18.600
Because this music
was not composed

00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:24.770
to be performed in opera, or to
be performed as a staged music.

00:09:24.770 --> 00:09:27.390
It's concert music,
which is staged.

00:09:27.390 --> 00:09:30.720
That's why this adding
of other elements

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:33.000
gives the music
different dimension.

00:09:35.850 --> 00:09:38.490
Another thing which is
interesting for Choregie

00:09:38.490 --> 00:09:43.560
is that performers are a
little bit different than we

00:09:43.560 --> 00:09:45.930
used to have them in opera.

00:09:45.930 --> 00:09:50.450
They used to use different
vocal techniques, not only

00:09:50.450 --> 00:09:54.050
Bel Canto, also ethnical,
extended vocal techniques.

00:09:54.050 --> 00:09:57.030
Musicians can be different.

00:09:57.030 --> 00:10:00.540
Another aspect for Choregie
is that we perform it

00:10:00.540 --> 00:10:06.260
not only in opera houses
and concert halls,

00:10:06.260 --> 00:10:09.740
but also in industrial
halls, in monasteries,

00:10:09.740 --> 00:10:13.550
in completely different
sociological environments.

00:10:16.890 --> 00:10:22.410
I think for me, Choregie is
a really, really good field

00:10:22.410 --> 00:10:24.900
and place for exploration.

00:10:24.900 --> 00:10:30.180
And it's a playground
for researching new music

00:10:30.180 --> 00:10:32.740
and new theater expressions.

00:10:32.740 --> 00:10:34.300
So I would like to make clear--

00:10:34.300 --> 00:10:38.610
Choregie, or music, new
music theater is not--

00:10:38.610 --> 00:10:44.490
is not opera, is not
musical, and is not operetta.

00:10:44.490 --> 00:10:51.160
So how did all this started?

00:10:51.160 --> 00:10:55.120
I was conductor of
Carmina Slovenica

00:10:55.120 --> 00:10:58.000
Ensemble and some others for--

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.730
Meredith already
mentioned-- for many years.

00:11:00.730 --> 00:11:04.240
We did a lot of
competitions, concert tours.

00:11:04.240 --> 00:11:10.140
And I start to add some other
elements to my performances.

00:11:10.140 --> 00:11:16.150
And I actually start to use
movement as a first element.

00:11:16.150 --> 00:11:18.490
Because in ethnical
music, in folk,

00:11:18.490 --> 00:11:23.680
folklore music, movement
and singing and instruments

00:11:23.680 --> 00:11:26.200
are so naturally connected.

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:28.310
And it was the first
contact with me

00:11:28.310 --> 00:11:33.940
how to change this classical
formation of choirs

00:11:33.940 --> 00:11:39.340
who were always kind of relics
of past, who stand in four rows

00:11:39.340 --> 00:11:42.190
into something
more communicative.

00:11:42.190 --> 00:11:46.390
So first thing was ethnical
music and movement.

00:11:46.390 --> 00:11:50.830
And second thing was, of
course, Greek tragedy,

00:11:50.830 --> 00:11:53.910
and the role of choir
in Greek tragedy,

00:11:53.910 --> 00:11:59.020
where chorus was about 20
to 50 people, of 20 people

00:11:59.020 --> 00:11:59.920
performers.

00:11:59.920 --> 00:12:00.670
They sing.

00:12:00.670 --> 00:12:01.920
They recite.

00:12:01.920 --> 00:12:02.950
They move.

00:12:02.950 --> 00:12:06.310
So they were part of the
performance, can make comments,

00:12:06.310 --> 00:12:08.770
who was the mirror
to the audience.

00:12:08.770 --> 00:12:13.570
And above all, they
serve as one entity.

00:12:13.570 --> 00:12:15.190
It was not a group
of many people,

00:12:15.190 --> 00:12:19.240
but they become one personality.

00:12:19.240 --> 00:12:22.930
So there were my two
first inspirations.

00:12:22.930 --> 00:12:26.530
And one of the
first such projects

00:12:26.530 --> 00:12:29.530
where movement was
incorporated into music,

00:12:29.530 --> 00:12:33.220
which is kind of ethnical
or new-age ethnical,

00:12:33.220 --> 00:12:36.762
was "Adiemus," which we
can see a little bit of it.

00:12:36.762 --> 00:12:37.428
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:37.428 --> 00:12:40.416
[SINGING - "KAYAMA"]

00:14:12.546 --> 00:14:13.150
[END PLAYBACK]

00:14:13.150 --> 00:14:15.670
A little bit weak, because
it's very old recording.

00:14:15.670 --> 00:14:19.720
But I would like to add
that this orchestra behind

00:14:19.720 --> 00:14:24.030
is international
orchestra, consists of

00:14:24.030 --> 00:14:28.300
only female, young
girls from entire region

00:14:28.300 --> 00:14:29.950
in central Europe.

00:14:29.950 --> 00:14:33.150
Because I was very much
inspired with [? Hospidalya ?]

00:14:33.150 --> 00:14:34.200
[? Veneziane. ?]

00:14:34.200 --> 00:14:36.520
I don't know if you're
familiar with this--

00:14:36.520 --> 00:14:40.660
that in old Venice there were
charitable institutions where

00:14:40.660 --> 00:14:43.660
they have female orchestras,
girls' orchestras,

00:14:43.660 --> 00:14:47.380
and girls' choirs,
who were there,

00:14:47.380 --> 00:14:51.850
who were abandoned children--
those who don't have parents--

00:14:51.850 --> 00:14:53.450
orphans.

00:14:53.450 --> 00:14:55.370
So I was inspired with these.

00:14:55.370 --> 00:14:59.922
That's why we actually
established this formation.

00:14:59.922 --> 00:15:01.410
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:15:01.410 --> 00:15:04.386
[SINGING - "KAYAMA"]

00:15:26.706 --> 00:15:27.710
[END PLAYBACK]

00:15:27.710 --> 00:15:32.330
Another very important
thing in my work

00:15:32.330 --> 00:15:36.050
is collective experience.

00:15:36.050 --> 00:15:38.090
Because it seems
that these crowds

00:15:38.090 --> 00:15:42.890
carry in themselves a
power and characteristics

00:15:42.890 --> 00:15:47.000
which by far exceed the mere sum
of psychological and physical

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.950
characteristics of
individuals in it.

00:15:49.950 --> 00:15:54.000
As you can see, I always
work with big groups.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:59.540
But the voice of the
collective we really like best

00:15:59.540 --> 00:16:00.800
is the voice of choir.

00:16:00.800 --> 00:16:04.430
Because choir is the only
bigger group activity

00:16:04.430 --> 00:16:08.580
that is not driven by any
ideology or economical,

00:16:08.580 --> 00:16:12.470
political, military,
or religion reasons.

00:16:12.470 --> 00:16:17.110
So choir is really a special
formation of human activity.

00:16:17.110 --> 00:16:20.300
And I am very fascinated
about one voice who

00:16:20.300 --> 00:16:24.650
becomes part of this
body of other voices,

00:16:24.650 --> 00:16:27.080
or all these bodies
together which become

00:16:27.080 --> 00:16:29.870
one body and one entity only.

00:16:29.870 --> 00:16:36.890
So choir has a very special
role and special power.

00:16:36.890 --> 00:16:38.362
Of course, it's
also very difficult

00:16:38.362 --> 00:16:40.070
to work with the choir,
because there are

00:16:40.070 --> 00:16:41.780
so many different characters.

00:16:41.780 --> 00:16:45.480
And you really have to work
a lot on team building.

00:16:45.480 --> 00:16:49.670
But at the end, when you manage
the established ensemble, which

00:16:49.670 --> 00:16:53.030
is a really strong
organism, then it really

00:16:53.030 --> 00:16:54.710
speaks very loud.

00:16:54.710 --> 00:16:57.210
So I would like
to share with you

00:16:57.210 --> 00:17:03.590
"Raua," just for a impression
of power of collective.

00:17:03.590 --> 00:17:06.578
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:17:06.578 --> 00:17:09.566
- [NON-ENGLISH SINGING]

00:18:47.450 --> 00:18:48.980
I would just like to add that--

00:18:48.980 --> 00:18:49.563
[END PLAYBACK]

00:18:49.563 --> 00:18:52.220
--they are singing
without being conducted.

00:18:52.220 --> 00:18:55.250
That's the very, very,
very special thing,

00:18:55.250 --> 00:19:00.080
to have 50 people being
so tuned emotionally

00:19:00.080 --> 00:19:04.010
and musically that they can
perform this complex music

00:19:04.010 --> 00:19:05.700
without being conducted.

00:19:05.700 --> 00:19:06.380
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:19:06.380 --> 00:19:09.824
- [NON-ENGLISH SINGING]

00:19:44.650 --> 00:19:46.130
[END PLAYBACK]

00:19:46.130 --> 00:19:49.080
Thank you.

00:19:49.080 --> 00:19:53.810
And the third very important
thing is, of course, voice.

00:19:53.810 --> 00:19:57.890
Because voice is always
center of my exploration.

00:19:57.890 --> 00:20:00.970
And voice in the
performance is impersonated,

00:20:00.970 --> 00:20:07.250
and really becomes a very,
very important manifestation.

00:20:07.250 --> 00:20:11.570
Actually, for me, it
becomes personality or more

00:20:11.570 --> 00:20:13.010
personalities.

00:20:13.010 --> 00:20:18.340
So I think that voice
has a special power

00:20:18.340 --> 00:20:23.380
to link to some specter of
emotions which we are not

00:20:23.380 --> 00:20:26.200
even aware that we carry in us.

00:20:26.200 --> 00:20:28.780
Some psycho-analytical
language is

00:20:28.780 --> 00:20:34.150
established when voices
make these soundscapes,

00:20:34.150 --> 00:20:36.280
and control the stage.

00:20:36.280 --> 00:20:40.780
But to understand the
voice better, of course,

00:20:40.780 --> 00:20:44.230
you need to research it, to
make a voice laboratorium,

00:20:44.230 --> 00:20:47.680
to really work on
every aspect of voice--

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:52.360
not only of beauty of the voice
like Bel Canto is, but also

00:20:52.360 --> 00:20:55.150
extended vocal
techniques to learn

00:20:55.150 --> 00:21:00.250
how other cultures use a
voice, from Eskimos to Balkan.

00:21:00.250 --> 00:21:02.740
So there are different ways
how you place your voice.

00:21:02.740 --> 00:21:07.150
But not only how to sing,
but also how to scream,

00:21:07.150 --> 00:21:10.210
cry, and all kind
of uses of voices.

00:21:10.210 --> 00:21:14.470
That's a really big
laboratorium which never ends.

00:21:14.470 --> 00:21:18.334
Maybe we can see Prasonata, just
a little bit how we actually--

00:21:18.334 --> 00:21:19.000
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:27.160
[INTERPOSING VOICES] how
we orchestrate sound poetry

00:21:27.160 --> 00:21:29.770
as a [INTERPOSING VOICES].

00:21:29.770 --> 00:22:23.785
- [SPEAKING SOUNDS]

00:22:23.785 --> 00:22:24.810
[END PLAYBACK]

00:22:24.810 --> 00:22:28.210
- So that was example of
sound poetry, actually.

00:22:28.210 --> 00:22:33.400
So how Choregie
projects are conceived--

00:22:33.400 --> 00:22:36.730
about process a little bit--

00:22:36.730 --> 00:22:41.540
the creation of
making these scores

00:22:41.540 --> 00:22:46.180
brings musical notion of
composing to all aspects.

00:22:46.180 --> 00:22:49.540
How we conceive of the piece,
how we perform it, of course,

00:22:49.540 --> 00:22:51.100
and stage it.

00:22:51.100 --> 00:22:54.670
So in Choregie, one
meta composition

00:22:54.670 --> 00:22:59.950
is created by positioning
different music, text, drama,

00:22:59.950 --> 00:23:04.240
and all kinds of visual elements
into one bigger composition.

00:23:04.240 --> 00:23:08.560
So treatment of all these voice,
text, movement, light, image,

00:23:08.560 --> 00:23:11.740
sound, gesture, and
all the elements

00:23:11.740 --> 00:23:16.510
of theatrical production is
based on musical principles

00:23:16.510 --> 00:23:18.760
and compositional techniques.

00:23:18.760 --> 00:23:21.580
That means that musical
thinking actually

00:23:21.580 --> 00:23:26.830
applies to the performance as
a whole, not only to music,

00:23:26.830 --> 00:23:28.870
as somebody would think.

00:23:28.870 --> 00:23:31.690
That's why relations
between elements

00:23:31.690 --> 00:23:35.110
is, let's say
musical vocabulary--

00:23:35.110 --> 00:23:39.610
polyphonic, imitation,
monophonic, homophonic,

00:23:39.610 --> 00:23:42.050
polyrhythmic, polytonal.

00:23:42.050 --> 00:23:45.955
So this musical thinking
is part of the process.

00:23:48.580 --> 00:23:54.340
Somehow, I can say that Choregie
is performance in no man's

00:23:54.340 --> 00:23:58.120
world, because it's
not the world of music,

00:23:58.120 --> 00:24:01.480
or world of drama, or dance.

00:24:01.480 --> 00:24:06.990
It's kind of adventure,
scenic adventure.

00:24:06.990 --> 00:24:11.860
Sometimes musicians ask
me if music is not enough,

00:24:11.860 --> 00:24:13.540
why do we stage it?

00:24:13.540 --> 00:24:17.350
We don't stage any music.

00:24:17.350 --> 00:24:20.440
When I get a score
or musical idea,

00:24:20.440 --> 00:24:22.900
I start to think
simultaneously--

00:24:22.900 --> 00:24:26.410
visual things, whatever
is part of the project.

00:24:26.410 --> 00:24:30.670
And if other elements
are organically here,

00:24:30.670 --> 00:24:32.530
then I go for Choregie project.

00:24:32.530 --> 00:24:35.050
If they're not here,
we do a concert,

00:24:35.050 --> 00:24:39.050
classical concert in a
hall, beautifully dressed,

00:24:39.050 --> 00:24:40.970
and normal thing.

00:24:40.970 --> 00:24:44.890
But contemporary
music, early music--

00:24:44.890 --> 00:24:50.410
they are very inspirative
for other elements

00:24:50.410 --> 00:24:53.120
to be part of the production.

00:24:53.120 --> 00:24:57.070
So I think that music becomes
interesting in other ways

00:24:57.070 --> 00:25:00.910
when it gets these references
in non-musical world.

00:25:00.910 --> 00:25:06.190
So inside of this field, when
music and non-music meets,

00:25:06.190 --> 00:25:08.770
then some different
dialogue starts.

00:25:08.770 --> 00:25:15.430
And because music and non-music,
they have different meanings,

00:25:15.430 --> 00:25:20.440
and coexistence somehow
brings new, third meaning,

00:25:20.440 --> 00:25:24.490
which is actually what
I'm interested in.

00:25:24.490 --> 00:25:29.620
But Choregie project--
that doesn't bring story

00:25:29.620 --> 00:25:31.300
in classical sense.

00:25:31.300 --> 00:25:34.150
So there is no
dominant story as we

00:25:34.150 --> 00:25:38.530
are used to have it in
opera, operetta, and musical.

00:25:38.530 --> 00:25:42.940
Of course, there is some
theme which was inspiration,

00:25:42.940 --> 00:25:47.470
but we don't have this
classical protagonist

00:25:47.470 --> 00:25:49.390
as we have it in opera.

00:25:49.390 --> 00:25:52.900
And there is no drama
between two protagonists.

00:25:52.900 --> 00:25:56.710
Nobody's killing, and
nobody's dying here.

00:25:56.710 --> 00:25:59.890
So there is no--

00:25:59.890 --> 00:26:04.090
dramatic is not-- we
don't get this dramatic

00:26:04.090 --> 00:26:09.090
from classical acting,
but from the way how

00:26:09.090 --> 00:26:13.270
music and other
elements are performed,

00:26:13.270 --> 00:26:16.780
and how they are understood.

00:26:16.780 --> 00:26:19.960
That's this dramatic
element, not the story

00:26:19.960 --> 00:26:21.700
and relationships.

00:26:21.700 --> 00:26:25.580
And we don't really have
some major protagonist

00:26:25.580 --> 00:26:29.290
who get all the attention
of the audience, what

00:26:29.290 --> 00:26:30.350
he's going to do.

00:26:30.350 --> 00:26:35.920
Usually, the main
protagonist is chorus.

00:26:35.920 --> 00:26:39.310
Even if there are five
people, a chamber group,

00:26:39.310 --> 00:26:41.260
they are not individuals.

00:26:41.260 --> 00:26:45.010
They are some part
of collective.

00:26:45.010 --> 00:26:49.960
That's why I mentioned that
collective is very important.

00:26:49.960 --> 00:26:54.670
So drama theater-- uh-huh.

00:26:54.670 --> 00:26:57.700
OK, how do I conceive
these things?

00:26:57.700 --> 00:27:02.100
As I mentioned, I develop
all elements simultaneously.

00:27:02.100 --> 00:27:05.890
So for example, for my project
which I'm developing here,

00:27:05.890 --> 00:27:09.250
I already make some paintings.

00:27:09.250 --> 00:27:12.850
Because these are basis
for visual elements.

00:27:12.850 --> 00:27:17.500
I already think how is
going to be set design,

00:27:17.500 --> 00:27:19.800
how is going to be movement.

00:27:19.800 --> 00:27:23.930
So all elements are
organically developed together.

00:27:23.930 --> 00:27:27.230
It's not only music, and
then, OK, now we know music--

00:27:27.230 --> 00:27:28.420
huh, what can we do?

00:27:28.420 --> 00:27:31.010
Shall we put some blue light?

00:27:31.010 --> 00:27:36.430
No, because light I understand
not as a source for light

00:27:36.430 --> 00:27:39.580
to be seen, but as a message.

00:27:39.580 --> 00:27:44.140
So all elements are
part of the score.

00:27:44.140 --> 00:27:45.580
Is that clear?

00:27:45.580 --> 00:27:47.500
Yes, cool.

00:27:47.500 --> 00:27:51.940
So ideas-- what's first?

00:27:51.940 --> 00:27:55.780
Sometimes, it's
a piece of music.

00:27:55.780 --> 00:27:59.740
Sometimes, it's
some question which

00:27:59.740 --> 00:28:02.380
I channel, which
I carry in myself,

00:28:02.380 --> 00:28:05.260
and I don't quite understand it.

00:28:05.260 --> 00:28:08.000
Usually, these are questions
which I don't understand.

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:10.180
And as I have like
50 projects, I

00:28:10.180 --> 00:28:12.490
don't really understand
much things in the world.

00:28:16.240 --> 00:28:18.820
But I like to do
things which don't

00:28:18.820 --> 00:28:21.970
have only one direct meaning.

00:28:21.970 --> 00:28:26.200
So I like to have
this open field

00:28:26.200 --> 00:28:30.310
for different interpretation
and for different receptions.

00:28:30.310 --> 00:28:35.290
So it's very challenging
to bring familiar things

00:28:35.290 --> 00:28:38.980
in new dress, and
in the new context,

00:28:38.980 --> 00:28:45.760
and give audiences and
performance as well a chance

00:28:45.760 --> 00:28:53.900
to interpret how they want,
which is somehow a big freedom,

00:28:53.900 --> 00:28:56.920
but as well, also,
big responsibility--

00:28:56.920 --> 00:29:01.780
to have this chance to
decide how to understand

00:29:01.780 --> 00:29:05.600
the piece, the project.

00:29:05.600 --> 00:29:09.470
So it seems exciting to allow
these familiar materials

00:29:09.470 --> 00:29:12.380
on which Choregie is
built the possibility

00:29:12.380 --> 00:29:16.280
to be discovered in new
ways again and again,

00:29:16.280 --> 00:29:21.080
and in new perspectives,
in various levels, and even

00:29:21.080 --> 00:29:22.100
various layers.

00:29:22.100 --> 00:29:27.050
You can always find,
and always uncover.

00:29:27.050 --> 00:29:33.410
So for example, here is
one piece-- just wait--

00:29:33.410 --> 00:29:38.120
Placebo, or Is There
One Who Would not Weep.

00:29:38.120 --> 00:29:43.670
This piece was based on very
well-known work Stabat Mater

00:29:43.670 --> 00:29:48.110
by Pergolesi,
Baroque composer, one

00:29:48.110 --> 00:29:52.100
of the most beautiful,
beautiful pieces in the history.

00:29:52.100 --> 00:29:54.620
And is based on medieval
texts about Mary,

00:29:54.620 --> 00:29:58.190
who is crying under
the cross when

00:29:58.190 --> 00:30:00.440
her son, Jesus, was crucified--

00:30:00.440 --> 00:30:03.080
so very well-known
medieval text.

00:30:03.080 --> 00:30:06.080
What we did is we made
new orchestration.

00:30:06.080 --> 00:30:08.270
So we don't have a
string orchestra,

00:30:08.270 --> 00:30:12.080
but we have one accordion,
and cello player,

00:30:12.080 --> 00:30:16.490
which is different
acoustical environment.

00:30:16.490 --> 00:30:22.610
And we re-question,
actually, mother Mary more

00:30:22.610 --> 00:30:28.030
than the situation of her
suffering below a cross.

00:30:28.030 --> 00:30:31.490
We question Mother Mary
as a social construct,

00:30:31.490 --> 00:30:35.030
and as an instrument of
supervision and control,

00:30:35.030 --> 00:30:40.490
or Mary as a symbolic construct
in which femininity is confined

00:30:40.490 --> 00:30:43.700
within the limits of
maternal, or Mother

00:30:43.700 --> 00:30:46.670
Mary as an object
of imaginary love,

00:30:46.670 --> 00:30:50.070
as a substitute of
suppressed male libido.

00:30:50.070 --> 00:30:54.140
So the Stabat Mater
which is so well known

00:30:54.140 --> 00:30:57.981
was somehow in new dress.

00:30:57.981 --> 00:30:58.480
Please.

00:30:58.480 --> 00:30:59.480
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

